<h2>Expert Tips</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700">
  <li><strong>Match Wine Weight to Chicken Preparation</strong> - The key to perfect chicken pairings lies in matching wine body to cooking method. Roasted chicken with crispy skin demands medium-bodied reds like Côtes du Rhône or Pinot Noir to complement the Maillard reaction flavors, while poached chicken breast pairs beautifully with lighter wines like Chablis or Grüner Veltliner that won't overpower the delicate protein.</li>

  <li><strong>Consider the Sauce, Not Just the Chicken</strong> - Chicken acts as a neutral canvas, making the sauce your primary pairing consideration. Creamy mushroom sauce calls for oaked Chardonnay or white Burgundy whose buttery notes echo the preparation, while tomato-based chicken cacciatore demands high-acid Italian reds like Sangiovese or Barbera d'Alba to cut through the acidity and complement the herbs.</li>

  <li><strong>Serve Whites Slightly Warmer for Chicken Dishes</strong> - Unlike seafood pairings, chicken dishes benefit from white wines served at 50-55°F rather than ice-cold. This temperature allows the wine's texture and complexity to shine through against chicken's mild flavor, particularly important for richer preparations like chicken cordon bleu with oaked Chardonnay or chicken almondine with Viognier.</li>

  <li><strong>Skip Decanting for Most Chicken Wines</strong> - The majority of wines perfect for chicken—young Pinot Noir, Chardonnay, Beaujolais, and most Rhône whites—are best served directly from the bottle. The exception is aged Burgundy (5+ years) paired with roasted chicken, which benefits from 30 minutes of decanting to open up its complex earthy notes that complement the bird's savory flavors.</li>

  <li><strong>Choose Burgundy Glasses for Optimal Chicken Pairings</strong> - The wide bowl of a Burgundy glass concentrates the delicate aromatics essential to both Pinot Noir and Chardonnay—the two most versatile chicken wines. This glass shape enhances the wine's fruit and earth notes while allowing proper aeration, crucial when pairing with herb-crusted or wine-braised chicken preparations.</li>

  <li><strong>Age Matters Less Than Freshness</strong> - Unlike bold red meat pairings, chicken dishes shine with younger, more vibrant wines. Drink Sancerre, Pouilly-Fuissé, or Oregon Pinot Noir within 2-3 years of vintage to capture their bright acidity and fresh fruit flavors that complement rather than compete with chicken's subtle taste profile.</li>

  <li><strong>Regional Pairing Rules Apply Perfectly</strong> - Follow the "what grows together, goes together" principle: Coq au Vin from Burgundy pairs with local Pinot Noir, while chicken marsala demands Sicilian whites like Grillo. These regional combinations have evolved over centuries because the wines naturally complement local cooking methods and ingredient combinations.</li>

  <li><strong>Time Your Wine Opening to the Cooking Method</strong> - Open light, fresh wines like Albariño or Muscadet just before serving quick-cooked chicken dishes to preserve their crisp character. However, for slow-braised chicken stews, open medium-bodied reds like Chinon or Dolcetto 15-20 minutes early, allowing them to breathe and develop flavors that will harmonize with the dish's concentrated, developed tastes.</li>
