<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between pairing wine with white meat versus dark meat chicken?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">White meat chicken breast has delicate flavors that pair beautifully with lighter wines like Chardonnay, Pinot Grigio, or light Pinot Noir, while dark meat (thighs and drumsticks) can handle bolder wines like Côtes du Rhône, Zinfandel, or oaked Chardonnay. The higher fat content and richer flavor in dark meat creates better balance with wines that have more body and intensity. Consider the cooking method too – grilled dark meat can even pair well with medium-bodied red wines like Sangiovese or Barbera.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I choose red or white wine with fried chicken?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Fried chicken's crispy, salty coating and rich flavors work exceptionally well with both sparkling wines and light to medium-bodied reds. Champagne or Prosecco cuts through the oil while cleansing the palate, making it the sommelier's top choice. For red wine lovers, try Beaujolais, Pinot Noir, or even a chilled Gamay – their bright acidity and moderate tannins complement the dish without overwhelming the chicken's flavor.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What wine pairs best with chicken in creamy sauces?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Rich, creamy chicken dishes like chicken Alfredo or coq au vin blanc require wines with enough acidity to cut through the cream and sufficient body to match the dish's richness. Oaked Chardonnay from Burgundy or California works beautifully, as does Viognier or white Rhône blends. The key is finding wines with both richness and bright acidity – avoid overly oaked wines that might clash with cream-based sauces.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can I serve the same wine with different chicken preparation methods?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">While versatile wines like unoaked Chardonnay or Pinot Noir can work across multiple preparations, matching the wine intensity to the cooking method creates better pairings. Grilled or blackened chicken needs bolder wines than poached chicken, and herb-crusted preparations call for wines that complement those specific seasonings. A good rule: the more intense the cooking method and seasoning, the more body and flavor complexity your wine should have.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the best budget wine option for chicken dinners under $15?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">For reliable, affordable chicken pairings, look for Portuguese Vinho Verde (crisp and food-friendly), Spanish Albariño, or domestic Pinot Grigio from Oregon or Washington. These wines typically retail for $10-15 and offer excellent acidity and clean flavors that complement most chicken preparations. French Côtes du Rhône blanc or Italian Vermentino also provide great value with enough complexity to elevate weeknight chicken dinners.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I decant wine when serving it with chicken?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Most wines paired with chicken don't require decanting since they're typically lighter-bodied whites or young, approachable reds. However, if you're serving an older red Burgundy with roasted chicken or a premium aged Chardonnay, 30 minutes of breathing time can help open up the wine's aromatics. For casual chicken dinners, simply opening the bottle 15-20 minutes before serving is sufficient for most wines to show their best.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What common mistakes should I avoid when pairing wine with chicken?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The biggest mistake is ignoring the sauce and seasonings – a wine that pairs perfectly with plain roasted chicken might clash terribly with chicken tikka masala or barbecue chicken. Also avoid serving wine too cold (whites) or too warm (reds), as temperature dramatically affects how the wine interacts with food. Don't automatically assume white wine is always best – many chicken dishes, especially those with mushrooms, herbs, or tomato-based sauces, are enhanced by light red wines.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibelier text-wine-700 mb-2">Are there good non-alcoholic alternatives that pair well with chicken?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Quality non-alcoholic wines from producers like Ariel or Fre can work well with chicken, particularly their Chardonnay and Cabernet offerings which maintain some wine-like complexity. For even better results, try premium grape juices like Welch's Reserve or sparkling grape ciders, which provide similar acidity and fruit flavors that complement chicken. Kombucha with fruity or herbal profiles also offers the acidity and effervescence that makes wine such a natural chicken pairing.</p>
  </div>
